In article <pooka.740280314@access> pooka@access.digex.net (Louis Emmet Mahoney) writes:
>wcs@anchor.ho.att.com (Bill Stewart +1-908-949-0705) writes:
>
>Silly question - since a OTP will generally be used only between two
>parties, is is feasible for the parties to agree (in a secure manner) to
>use two copies of some commercial audio or data CD?  Presumably they are
>identical (within manufacturing tolerances). 

Music has much too much structure to it.

This is like doing an XOR with a LFSR or, heaven forbid, a PRNG like
rand() in most programming languages.  It looks nice and random, but
a cryptanalyst will have a field day.

>Alternatively, use a common and mutually-agreeable data CD, e.g. "the DAK
>discount CIA Fact Book, 1984" or such ?

Maybe, but if you encode voice data you will have pauses, if only for
breath.  During that period your "CIA Fact Book" will be transmitted
(nearly) in the clear, giving the spooks insight into your data source.

